href="jonmsterling.xml"
type="local"
addr="jonmsterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:parent>jms-005V</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>This release adds support for generating subsections from transclusions obtained by a query the forest; this can be used to produce topical bibliographies.</fr:p>
  
  <fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="true"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>804</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon><fr:addr>jms-006A</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-006A.xml</fr:route><fr:title>A conjunctive query node</fr:title><fr:date><fr:year>2023</fr:year><fr:month>7</fr:month><fr:day>20</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
href="jonmsterling.xml"
type="local"
addr="jonmsterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:parent>jms-0066</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>The following code will generate a subsection entitled “featured talks” containing the appropriate items as collapsed subtrees:</fr:p><fr:pre>\scope{
  \put\transclude/title{featured talks}
  \query{
    \query/and{
      \query/author{jonmsterling}
      \query/taxon{reference}
      \query/tag{featured}
    }
  }
}</fr:pre><fr:p>Under the hood, a query node is an “anonymous transclusion” and can therefore be <fr:link
href="jms-0067.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-0067">configured using the same options as other transclusions</fr:link>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
</fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter><fr:contributions></fr:contributions><fr:context><fr:tree
